data.name: Hello Tokyo
data.description:
This video was shot over a 5 day trip to Tokyo in January 2016. 

It was my first time visiting Japan, a place I had always wanted to see. With a population of 35 million, Tokyo is the largest metropolitan area in the world. Due to this, I soon realised how lively and energetic this city really is.

I decided to take my camera and explore this fascinating city so rich in culture, tradition and innovation.

Equipment and Software used:

Canon 5D Mark III
Tamron 24-70 F/2.8 Di VC
Samyang 14mm T3.1
Edelkrone Slider & Action Module
Adobe After Effects 
Twixtor
Lightroom
LR Timelapse

Music: Bonobo - Sapphire

data.name: Hello World! Processing
data.description:
Hello World! Processing is a documentary on creative coding that explores the role that ideas such as process, experimentation and algorithm play in this creative field featuring artists, designers and code enthusiasts.  Based on a series of interviews to some of the leading figures of the Processing open programming platform community, the documentary is built itself as a continuous stream of archived references, projects and concepts shared by this community.

It is the first chapter of a documentary series on three programming languages -Processing, Open Frameworks y Pure data- that have increased the role of coding in the practice of artists, designers and creators around the world.

The series explores the creative possibilities expanded by these open source tools and the importance of their growing online communities.

See more information at http://www.hello-world.cc

data.name: Hello Brooklyn
data.description:
Dans le New-York des annes 50, cinq jeunes gens dambulent dans les rues de Brooklyn, se promnent  vlo le long des alles de Central Park, et flnent sur la plage de Coney Island.

New York, in the 50's, five young people are wandering in Brooklyn streets, riding bicycles accross the alleys of Central Park and loafing around on the beach of Coney Island.

Film ralis comme court mtrage d'ouverture pour le Festival International du Film d'Animation (FIFA) d'Annecy 2011, par Alice BISSONET, Benjamin MOREAU, Corentin PENLOUP, Marion ROUSSEL, Louis THOMAS, tudiants de la formation Concepteur et ralisateur de films d'animation (2e anne)  GOBELINS, l'cole de l'image. 

37 secondes.

Distribution :
La distribution des films produits par GOBELINS, l'cole de l'image est assure par L'Agence du court mtrage. Contact : f.keller@agencecm.com.

user.name: GOBELINS pro
user.bio:
Acteur de rfrence dans la communication numrique et interactive, GOBELINS, lcole de limage est un tablissement de la Chambre de commerce et dindustrie de rgion Paris Ile-de-France. Elle forme, depuis plus de cinquante ans, aux mtiers de la photographie (1963), de la communication et des industries graphiques (1969), du cinma danimation (1975), de la vido (1984), du multimdia (1991) et du jeu vido (2011). Elle forme chaque anne 800 lves en formation initiale et 1700 stagiaires en formation continue.

GOBELINS, l'cole de l'image is the pionner school in digital communication and interactive design. For nearly 50 years, GOBELINS has trained the talent of tomorrow in the fields of photography, both interactive and graphic design, animated filmmaking, enternainement and immersive animation as well as the communication and graphic industries. GOBELINS is a vibrant community 700 students coming from all around the world.

Our philosophy is tu support the freedom of the students to express their creativity!

data.name: Hello FutureLearners!
data.description:
Meet four of the the hundreds and thousands of learners on FutureLearn: Guljan from Iraq, Tony and Lynn from the UK, and Anzela from Latvia. Read more about the video here: https://about.futurelearn.com/blog/hello-futurelearners/

FutureLearn offers free online learning from universities and cultural institutions from all around the world - sign up to FutureLearn or browse courses at https://www.futurelearn.com.

All of the conversations featured in this video were recorded over the phone, so we dont know what Anzela, Guljan, Tony and Lynn look like (and who knows, maybe they really do have blue and purple hair). But we worked closely with the audio material to build visual characters, using Aardmans Creature Comfortswork from 1990 as inspiration.

Richard Hogg (who designed the PlayStation game, Hohokum and lots of other great things) designed the characters and the rest of the film. Mummu were our animation partners.

user.name: M.Marin
user.bio:
Bleepstreet since 1998 / 8-bit data-futurism on vinyl happy groove destruction 
Bleepstreet likes 8-bit technology and groovy, filthy and raw data action. After a few years break 
Bleepstreet is now back to go beyond 8-bit machines as gimmicks. We make gritty electro, playful 
pop, slow harsh beats, techno, data rock, breakcore and so on, and we dont see computers as mere 
slaves under our control. The soundchip of a C-64 is a beast that cannot be fully tamed! 
 
With our new music programs and hardware modifications, Bleepstreet aims at showcasing what 
ber nostalgic videogame nerds dont. Live performances with real-time generated music, DJ-sets 
with the funkiest floppy music, VJs with the hottest megapixels, workshops for the interested, lec- 
tures for the academics, audiovisual chill-out sessions for the psychonauts, or maybe showing you 
some highlights of the strange demoscene subculture.
